{
  "Identity & Zero Matrices": "",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "",
  "What is the 2 x 2 identity matrix?": "",
  "The 2 x 2 identity matrix has 1s on the main diagonal and 0s elsewhere: [[1, 0], [0, 1]]. It is denoted I_2.": "",
  "What is [[3, 5], [1, 2]] * I_2?": "",
  "Multiplying any square matrix by the identity matrix of the same size returns the original matrix: A * I = A.": "",
  "What is the 3 x 3 zero matrix?": "",
  "The 3 x 3 zero matrix has all nine entries equal to zero: [[0,0,0],[0,0,0],[0,0,0]].": "",
  "What is A + O, where O is the zero matrix of the same size as A?": "",
  "The zero matrix is the additive identity. Adding it to any matrix A of the same dimensions leaves A unchanged: A + O = A.": "",
  "What is A * O, where A is 2 x 3 and O is the 3 x 4 zero matrix?": "",
  "Multiplying any matrix by a zero matrix (with compatible dimensions) gives a zero matrix. The result has the outer dimensions: 2 x 4.": "",
  "What is I_3 * [[2], [5], [-1]]?": "",
  "The identity matrix leaves any vector unchanged when multiplied: I_3 * v = v. So the result is [[2], [5], [-1]].": "",
  "What is I_2 * I_2?": "",
  "The identity matrix multiplied by itself gives the identity matrix: I * I = I. This is because I is the multiplicative identity.": "",
  "For an n x n identity matrix I_n, what is the value of entry i_{2,3} when n >= 3?": "",
  "In the identity matrix, i_{j,k} = 1 only when j = k (on the diagonal). Since 2 is not equal to 3, the entry i_{2,3} = 0.": "",
  "What is the 'identity matrix'?": "",
  "The identity matrix I_n is the n x n square matrix with 1s on the main diagonal and 0s in all other positions. It is the multiplicative identity for matrix multiplication.": "",
  "What is the 'zero matrix'?": "",
  "The zero matrix is a matrix in which every entry is 0. It can have any dimensions (m x n) and serves as the additive identity for matrix addition.": "",
  "What is the 'scalar matrix' cI_n?": "",
  "The scalar matrix cI_n is obtained by multiplying the identity by scalar c, placing c on every diagonal entry and 0 elsewhere. Multiplying by cI scales a matrix by c.": "",
  "What is the 'trace' of the n x n identity matrix I_n?": "",
  "The trace is the sum of diagonal entries. Since I_n has n ones on the diagonal, the trace is 1 + 1 + ... + 1 = n.": "",
  "What is the determinant of the n x n identity matrix?": "",
  "The determinant of the identity matrix is always 1, regardless of the matrix size n. This follows from the product of its diagonal entries (all 1s).": "",
  "A factory's production amounts are stored in a 3 x 4 matrix P. During a holiday shutdown, all production is zero, represented by the zero matrix O of the same size. What is P + O?": "",
  "Adding the zero matrix to any matrix of the same dimensions returns the original matrix: P + O = P. The factory's production data is unaffected.": "",
  "A network router initializes its routing table as a zero matrix of size 10 x 10. This means no routes exist yet between any of the 10 nodes. If the router receives data and multiplies it by this zero routing matrix, what is the result?": "",
  "Multiplying any vector by the zero matrix gives the zero vector. This represents no data being transmitted, which makes sense since no routes are configured.": "",
  "A quality control system scales measurement readings by multiplying by 5I_3, where I_3 is the 3 x 3 identity matrix. If a sensor reading is [[2], [7], [4]], what is the amplified reading?": "",
  "5I_3 = [[5,0,0],[0,5,0],[0,0,5]]. Multiplying: 5I_3 * [[2],[7],[4]] = [[10],[35],[20]]. The scalar matrix scales each component by 5.": "",
  "What does 'multiplicative identity' mean in the context of matrices?": "",
  "The multiplicative identity is the identity matrix I, which satisfies A * I = I * A = A for any square matrix A of the same size.": "",
  "What does it mean for the zero matrix to be an 'absorbing element' for multiplication?": "",
  "The zero matrix absorbs in multiplication: for any conformable matrix A, A * O = O and O * A = O (though the dimensions of the resulting zero matrices may differ).": "",
  "An encryption system multiplies a message vector m by an encoding matrix E to encrypt, then by a decoding matrix D to decrypt. For the system to work, what must D * E equal?": "",
  "For decryption to recover the original message, D * (E * m) = (D * E) * m = I * m = m. Thus D * E must equal the identity matrix.": "",
  "A machine learning model is initialized with a weight matrix set to the zero matrix. A data analyst says this is problematic for neural network training. What immediate effect does multiplying inputs by this zero weight matrix have?": "",
  "Multiplying any input vector by the zero matrix produces the zero vector. All information from the inputs is lost, which prevents the network from learning useful features.": "",
  "A database stores null sales data as a zero matrix. At the end of Q1, actual sales matrix S is added to the initialized zero matrix. A new intern worries this addition changed the data. Did it?": "",
  "Adding the zero matrix to any matrix returns the original: S + O = S. The sales data is preserved exactly as it was.": "",
  "An image processing filter is represented as a 3 x 3 matrix applied to pixel neighborhoods. The 'no filter' option uses the identity matrix. If a pixel neighborhood is [[120], [200], [50]], what does the identity filter output?": "",
  "The identity matrix preserves the input: I * [[120],[200],[50]] = [[120],[200],[50]]. The 'no filter' option correctly returns the original pixel values.": ""
}